Date: Sun, 17 Jan 1999 12:42:30 +0800
From: Yap T G <tgyap@pc.jaring.my>

With regards to comments on the recent epidemic paralysis by Dr.John Marr,
I beg to disagree that lathyrism is "of historical interest". The Nepalese
epidemic strikes one as having dietary origins and might have elements of
nutritional deficiency. Certainly it bears some similarities with lathyrism.
Legumes of Lathyrus sativa, called "khesari dhal" are eaten among South
Asian populations either as a stable food or supplementary food item. I
remember editing an article for a magazine 15 years ago in which a Bangla
Deshi correspondent described the problem of lathyrism as existing in
endemic pockets. The toxic component of the legume was isolated as an
anutrient-amino acid (beta-N-oxalylamino-alanine). The toxin causes
demyelination of the lateral columns of the spinal cord, giving rise to a
clinical picture of spastic paraplegia and 'scissors gait' of upper motor
neuron involvement. Not being an expert myself in these fields I stand to
be corrected.
Especially in diseases in which culture and local dietary habits are
prominent, ProMED-mail may do well to learn from local scientists of the
region. More recent reference or authorities can be sought outside of that
below:
Suresh Roa Aror: "Diseases of the CNS" in 'Diseases of Children in the
Subtropics and Tropics', 4th Ed., Edward Arnold, Kent (1991).
--
Tuan-Gee YAP, MBBS, PhD.,
International Medical College,
Petaling Jaya, Malaysia.
e-mail: tgyap@pc.jaring.my
[As always, we value the contributions of scientists of all cultures and
localities. Indeed, we would not be able to operate ProMED-mail as an
international list without their help. I have submitted Dr. Yap's comment
to Dr. John Marr for his response, and it appears below. - Mod.ES
