Date: Sun, 17 Jan 1999 16:09:32 EST
From: Dr. John Marr <JSM04@aol.com>

In response to Tuan-Gee YAP, MBBS, Ph.D.'s comment on lathyrism:
He is certainly correct that lathyrism is not an historical disease -- it
continues to cause illness and death in many parts of the world. The
citation I used came from the book, "Poisonous Plants of the United States
and Canada", Kingsbury, JM, Prentice-Hall, 1964, and was in the context of
poisonous plants in these two countries. It is a somewhat dated text, and
I wish it would be updated. But, it is still accurate for North America
toxic flora.
Of interest, another once toxic plant -- white snakeroot or richweed,
(Eupatorium rugosum) -- was a common plant intoxicant dating to the
American Revolution. It caused a disease in animals and humans known as
"trembles' or "milk sickness", respectively. The latter term was used
since the toxin could be transmitted via a sick cow's milk to humans.
Kingsbury states, "...It is often stated that this disease was responsible
for the death of Abraham Lincoln's mother." (p. 339)
In another book, "Poisonous Plants of the United States", Muenscher, WC,
Colliers Books, 1975, the author states, "This annual herb ( sic. Lathyrus
savitus) is grown as a forage plant mainly in southern Europe and parts of
India where it seeds are used at times of scarcity for human food." (p.
134).
A quick review of the literature on PubMED reveals 642 articles published
on lathyrism in the last 20 years. In particular, two recent papers:
"Evidence of osteolathyrism among patients suffering from neurolathyrism in
Bangladesh." Haque, A. et al., Nat Toxins 1997;5 (1): 43-46; & " Toxic
models of upper motor neuron disease." Ludolph, AC, Spencer, PS. J Neurol
Sci. 1996; Aug; 139 Suppl: 53-59.
I certainly appreciate the citation to Suresh Roa Aror -- it is recent and
deals with lathyrism outside the U.S/Canada. In search in amazon.com, I
found a few recent books on poisonous plants, but they also dealt with
either a small number of intoxications/poisonings and/or were limited to
the U.S.
I wish to thank Dr. Tuan-Gee for the correction. I also believe that
naturally occurring toxins from plants and animals seem to fall between the
cracks when one thinks of causes for outbreaks which appear to be
infectious in nature or cause by chemicals.
